This is my first year programming, and we are using Java on a swerve drive. We are experiencing a problem with teleop and auto functioning. When we enable the robot with our code, the teleop works perfectly fine. When we try to enable auto after we disable the teleop, the wheels move around randomly. There is one line of code, that when removed, fixes the problem with the auto, but makes the teleop do nothing. that line is “m_robotContainer.setDefault();” inside of teleopinit.

We have tried commenting out the setDefault command, and it does make the auto work. But then the teleop stops working. Also, the auto we are using is on a command, and works with a button on a controller during teleop. So I am led to believe that the auto itself is not the problem

setDefault is called in robotcontainer

A subsystem’s default command must require it’s respective subsystem, and will always run. This means that any other command that wants to use this subsystem must require it.

In your linked code, it doesn’t look like the current auto requires the swerve subsystem, which could be the cause of your issue.

You can install do-nothing default commands in auto, then only install the default commands you want to use in teleop. Do this in auto/teleopInit. I have seen this come up as a CSA, but never really had/took the time to sort it out properly. However, this does make things work. The default command should be lower priority, so that it only runs when nothing else is runnable. I think I saw at least one instance where the requirements were there, but this problem was still present. But, things get kind of crazy at events sometimes, and there’s usually not time to really sort things out once teams are running…

You should only initialize a single instance of you Swerve subsystem in RobotContainer and pass that single instance to all of you commands. In your auto command, you initialize another instance of your Swerve subsystem and use it for your autos, which probably means the auto command is applying to this second instance and not the original one, which makes you auto command appear to not work.

Your RobotContainer is trying to use AutoBalanceAuto, and the code snippet you posted here was fixing AutoBalance.

You need to have the following fundamentals when you’re working with Command-Based:

  1. All your commands must call addRequirements() to all their subsystems they are using. In your github, that is currently not the case. Go fix all of them to do that.
  2. All your subsystems should be instantiated in your RobotContainer and passed to the constructors or your commands via dependency injection (or through command factories).

If you structure your code that way, you won’t run into the problem you’re seeing which seems to be relative to the fact that your command group is requiring a different instance of your subsystem.

The CommandRobot template project sets things up for you this way where the Subsystems are declared final and private.
